{"cursor":"36514","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'Smith chart', invented by Phillip H. Smith (1905â1987), Smith, P. H.;\nTransmission Line Calculator; Electronics, Vol. 12, No. 1, pp 29-31, January\n1939 Smith, P. H.; An Improved Transmission Line Calculator;\nElectronics, Vol. 17, No. 1, p 130, January 1944 is a graphical aid or\nnomogram designed for electrical and electronics engineers specializing in radio\nfrequency (RF) engineering to assist in solving problems with transmission lines\nand matching circuits. Ramo, Whinnery and Van Duzer (1965); \"Fields and\nWaves in Communications Electronics\"; John Wiley & Sons; pp 35-39. ISBN\nUse of the Smith chart utility has grown steadily over the years and it is still\nwidely used today, not only as a problem solving aid, but as a graphical\ndemonstrator of how many RF parameters behave at one or more frequencies, an\nalternative to using tabular information. The Smith chart can be used to\nsimultaneously display multiple parameters including impedances, admittances,\nreflection coefficients, S_{nn}\\, scattering parameters, noise\nfigure circles, constant gain contours and regions for unconditional stability,\nincluding mechanical vibrations analysis. Pozar, David M. (2005); Microwave\nEngineering, Third Edition (Intl. Ed.); John Wiley & Sons, Inc.; pp 64-71. ISBN\n0-471-44878-8. Gonzalez, Guillermo (1997); Microwave Transistor\nAmplifiers Analysis and Design, Second Edition; Prentice Hall NJ; pp 93-103.\nISBN 0-13-254335-4. The Smith chart is most frequently used at or within\nthe unity radius region. However, the remainder is still mathematically\nrelevant, being used, for example, in oscillator design and stability\nanalysis. Gonzalez, Guillermo (1997) (op. cit);pp 98-101\n","linknr":454,"url":"Smith_Chart","recorded":1362480252,"links":37,"instances":["mathematics","angle","mathematics","information","electronics","mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","number","signal_processing","electronics","geometry","unit"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Electrical engineering","Charts"],"headings":["Overview","Mathematical basis","Using the Smith chart to solve conjugate matching problems with distributed components","Using the Smith chart to analyze lumped element circuits","3D Smith chart","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/6/1/a610a6b3a874cac369d2a6057d50b187.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Visual_Smith_Chart.png/220px-Visual_Smith_Chart.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7a/Smith_chart_gen.svg/250px-Smith_chart_gen.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/74/NetworkAnalyzer.jpg/400px-NetworkAnalyzer.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Smith_chart_explanation.svg/500px-Smith_chart_explanation.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/9/3/193aa966b0ae0f6c041d27e11206077f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/b/8/5/b8516613fdd1d33afa26594debd4c782.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/9/3/e93dc1b0d1ce5cb8810ce309f8c01653.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/e/6/3e6ab7f65407026600335e518e8bd70c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/4/9/549c9d515a77b47dd2d5a28c37abe77e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/d/0/1d07326150b64e7bf5cc9ef2c302be6e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/e/6/3e6ab7f65407026600335e518e8bd70c.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/9/3/193aa966b0ae0f6c041d27e11206077f.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/2/7/a/27ac1338271c3a36591d67f96a288df8.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/4/2/f/42f228ee37ba6b62af6e1ee047a6471e.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/e/d/f/edf1cef8a3c34087d9afe8d94fcea475.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/9/2/69226a99e43354